commitResults.messageBody:
Tasks are not persistent between sessions.

Persistent storage allows users to pick up where they left off.

Let's introduce saving & loading to `./data/duke.txt`.
Use OS-independent file handling to ensure compatibility.
Create reader & writer classes to abstract out the IO responsibility.

This approach ensures data durability and enhances the chatbot's usability.
It supports task management across sessions without user intervention.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add date and time parsing for task deadlines
commitResults.messageBody:
Chatbot treats deadline commands as plain strings.

Add parsing of strings to convert them to LocalDateTime obj,
as well as error handling for wrongly formatted inputs.

This approach is taken for clarity and ease of use, and
allows for future use of the java.time API for timezone
related operations.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add and automate build with Gradle
commitResults.messageBody:
Project build are being managed manually.
Have to manually compile all the java file.

Inefficient and slow, manual process as well.
Could be running outdated .class files if
not done properly.

Add Gradle from master branch by merge.

Gradle helps with setting up the Duke application
and helps to automate the manual tasks.

Testing is very manual, by printing out
variable and confirming each input by
hand.

This is not scalable and not practical
when the codebase becomes much bigger
and there are more dependencies in the
future.

Add JUnit tests for certain classes
based on importance. To ensure that the
expected behaviour is as observed and
does not change with further development.

JUnit tests are great as it is integrated
with gradle, thus becoming easy to maintain
and run.

commitResults.messageTitle: Package main application into JAR file
commitResults.messageBody:
The application needs to be compiled and
ran with java from the terminal or IDE.

This will make the application difficult
more difficult to run for end users.

Package main application into java using
shadowjar, allow us to run the application
with a simple java - jar <filename>.

This will allow for an easier time to
test and use the application.

Not all classes have completed Javadoc comments.

This makes reading the code confusing and time-
consuming as you have to understand the code before
making sense of it's purpose.

Add JavaDoc to each class and most methods.

This improves code readability and maintainability
as it allows readers to quickly understand what
the class and methods are used for.

The Java codes in the application do not
adhere to the coding standard.

This may result in the code being hard
to read or understand, and therefore even
harder to maintain

Change codes to adhere to coding standard,
imported checkstyler and used Gradle to
run.

Allow gradle to check Java code for
readability and makes code more readable.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add find command to Chatbot application
commitResults.messageBody:
There is no find command in the application,
users have to list all task and search manually.

This is no intuitive and causes the user to
manually search for his/her task.

Add find command to filter task for the user.

Allows user to quickly find the task they are
looking for.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add CheckStyle to check for consistency
commitResults.messageBody:

commitResults.messageTitle: Utilize Java Enums for different types
commitResults.messageBody:
The ActionTask uses strings to represent different
types of actions. This allows it to handle a fixed
set of variables.

This could lead to errors and makes the code hard
to implement, as developers have to read and match
the words for the corresponding actions.

Let's change the String list into an Enum, and use
it to indicate the respective action type of
ActionTask.

This will allow only defined types to be created,
enforcing proper type security and ensuring that
it is easy to define and debug.
Utilize Java Enums for different types

The code does not sort Tasks according to their
deadlines or start date.

This may lead users to miss their deadlines as
they are not chronologically ordered.

Implement comparator to each of the Tasks's
subclass.

This allows us to sort the Tasks according to
their urgency, if applicable, and name.

The code has no ability to sort the Tasks
for the user to see it chronologically.

This is not intuitive and the user may
miss important deadlines due to this.

Implement a Comparator on each 
Task and override it's compareTo
method.

This will allow me to sort the storage
list by the respective Tasks, allowing
users to see their Tasks in a
chronological order.
